# Line endings. Every checkout gets LF in the working tree, on every
# platform, because several suites assert byte- and column-exact geometry:
# tests/fixtures/llm-diagram.md is read verbatim by the diagram repair
# tests, and the Mermaid lexer keeps its source verbatim for on-diagram
# edit offsets. Git's Windows default (core.autocrlf=true) rewrites those
# files to CRLF on checkout, which shifts every offset by one byte per
# line; that is what failed DiagramRepairTests on the windows-2022 runner
# while the LF local clone passed.
* text=auto eol=lf

# Windows batch files are the exception: the shell wants CRLF.
*.bat text eol=crlf

# Vendored code keeps upstream's bytes, including its line endings: two
# tinyxml2 sources ship with CRLF, and normalizing them would make the
# tree differ from the release the SBOM names. Nothing under third_party
# is offset-sensitive to the suites.
third_party/** -text

# Binary assets: never touched, never diffed as text. text=auto detects
# most of these, but naming them keeps the fonts and media unambiguous.
*.png binary
*.ico binary
*.icns binary
*.svg text eol=lf
*.ttf binary
*.otf binary
*.wav binary
*.mp4 binary
